  <article id="comment-1048792" class="single-comment">
    <div>
      <header>
        <div>
                      <a href="/users/ztcantrl/comments" title="View ztcantrl&#039;s profile">ztcantrl</a>                                <time class="created" title="2011-09-22T14:20:01+00:00">Sep 22nd 2011 14:20 GMT</time>
        </div>
      </header>
      <div class="comment-body"><p>As another reader stated above: this really is a proof of concept research deal. I wouldn't expect this to become an everyday use of everyone's iPhone. However, to those pointing out that it fuels distracted driving and thus would increase accidents, fatalities, and even have the opposite of the intended effect: while it may be true that looking at the phone on the dash for a couple of seconds could distract you, isn't texting the same way? Almost everyone nowadays texts while driving. If someone wants to use this app, this takes the phone out of their hands and puts it on the dash, where they won't be texting; those who don't use the app will probably be texting anyway, still distracted. Also, I feel like it's just like having a Garmin or TomTom mounted on the dash. Only those who allow it to be a distraction will be distracted by it. Wouldn't you rather have a fellow drivers glance at their phone that sits on the dash (and possibly slow down based on what the app tells them) in the same place your own GPS sits as they approach the traffic light rather than looking down into their lap sending an unimportant text message about how hungover they are?</p>
<p>In the end, though, this is still proof-of-concept research that could one day be put into the technology systems of vehicles themselves in order to improve efficiency.</p>
</div>
      <footer class="clearfix">
